@bobby k i love the way it sounds on a modern record. the right amount and kind of clipping compresses the sound in a way that a compressor or limiter doesn't do. 

when i'm making music with drum samples (which is almost everything) the clipping of the music buss and/or mix buss creates the right kind of aggressive cohesion i'm looking for. when it works the best, it softens transients the right amount while glueing the excitement of programmed music together.

clipping doesn't work nearly as well for me when i have organic drums, because the transients are much more delicate in live performed drum track. i also don't clip much when it's an acoustic song or not dominated by programmed drums. clipping tends to work best for me when the dominant transients are consistent

@Zakhiggins https://youtu.be/brXOrmgPCfE

These loudness videos are helpful for understanding the concept. But also, I don’t take my cue on how loud to make my mixes from any YouTuber/podcaster/plugin company/streaming platform. Cue into what your reference mixes sound like in tidal on hifi with normalization off. Route that into your DAW with a virtual output and you can compare LUFS on your favorite meters. The truth is there are no standards and trying to beat/cheat every loudness algorithm is folly. Make good shit that sounds like your favorite un-normalized records. 

Something else I have done, grab some CDs from a local library of your favorite records and put those wavs into a meter or RX and see what the pros are actually printing out loudness and peak wise.

