@Eric Martin thanks for your reply man, re: clippers vs compression......yes i am familiar with that. I dont use compression for dynamics control either....you may have heard of the "clip to zero" strategy? i do a similar thing but then output my limiters/clippers at -6db instead of 0. Its similar to what johns doing just catching peaks and not squashing the life out of everythin....mike dean does it too IIRC. 

Re: spectral shaper : I didnt actually spot jon using his spectral shaper in that 1-6khz region, i saw it in the low mids....so having heard you and @oaklandmatt both mention it ...it seems hes defo already using this high mid scoop trick then! Ill still research the maths of the lufs algo because i like to really understand the psycho-acoustics and science of these sorts of things. Im after the ultimate mix in this life, lol .....i come from underground club music, where drums and bass and a sweet vocal are everything so its a constant balance/re-balance between lows/mids and highs as i learn more advanced techniques

..re: jons mix yesterday and clipping, and you mention clipping the attack portion of a sounds adsr , did you notice how much he uses transient shapers on almost everything? v clever. Personally, i love transients and fight hard to keep them and jons trick of putting a transient shaper after a clipper/limiter has been a revelation....(thanks @oaklandmatt , that gem came from your LWMR) .....bruce swedien said compression is for children, and i believe he evangelised about not killing transients ...i love a transient shaper and a clipper ....compressor , not so much.

@NoahNeedleman @cian riordan @Will Melones This is awesome, thank you for your thoughts!

@NoahNeedleman Wouldn't have considered drum tuning changes. I'd be thinking about that over takes of a studio track, and flipping playlists makes it easy to check on the same section, but in this context it's the sort of thing that would've tripped me up. Like, why is the snare thwacking in song 1, but it's thwocking in song 20? Would be easy to second guies, start EQing again and ruin the rest of the show. Absolutely if you're chatting to Kaplan, it'd be great to hear - I'm sure the Discord generally would appreciate but I'd love to get his inside track, please!

@cian riordan Great shout on mindset, thank you. As @Will Melones mentioned, the energy is already great so it's not like I'm going to have to do a lot of heavy lifting. In the words of @BatMeckley (referring to the OP-1 vs Ableton), sounds like this is one to ride like a surfboard rather than drive like a bus.

@Nomograph Mastering  I'm 100% with you on serving the art, but I’d love to hear your take on something—what about when the artist straight-up doesn’t care about the art, the vision, or any of that? When every production choice, note, and mix decision is purely driven by the desire to be successful, get accepted, sell more, etc.? Nothing to do with the music itself

I get that, at the end of the day, we’re providing a service, and the goal is a happy client—no questions asked about their motivations. But if you really love music, art, and expression, it can be tough to work with someone making artistic choices for every reason except the art itself

What’s your take on that? I try to be pragmatic and put on my “service provider” hat when dealing with those kinds of clients, but…

@Juliette Ok having heard the track, there’s a solo synth bass in there which is well designed sonically, when that drops out and the bass guitar comes back in, everything from about 60-70 cycles and below disappears except for the kick. So yeah I’d first try pumping low end into it, be it with EQ or subharmonic, followed by some (a lot) of compression. I’m sure better people here have a better way to do this. 

The DI itself doesn’t have any overtones other than stuff you’re finding unflattering, so you could try mult’ing the DI signal out to an amp sim (even some guitar amps work here) to fill out the spectrum that the guitars aren’t fulfilling 

I’d also say the bass drum could use some augmenting of the low end  and maybe a bit of length in order to emphasise that impact. Because the synth bass atm has all the power, and isn’t omnipresent, so it’s leaving the rest of the arrangement even _more_ neutered as a result
